Whatâ€™s Cooking

Sirui Zhou

12/05/2017

This project is from Kaggle competition. The goal is to distinguish the category of a dishâ€™s cuisine based on a list of its ingredients.

# load packages
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(methods)
library(stringi)
library(smodels)
library(tokenizers)
library(wordcloud)
library(viridis)

Know My Data

The data was provided by Yummly, a website for users to find their desired recipe. The data is stored in the JSON files. The first step is to use fromJson function from the jsonlite package to convert the JSON file to a data frame.

library(jsonlite)
recipe <- fromJSON("train.json", flatten = TRUE)

As shown, the raw data for ingredients is a char list rather than the textual data. Letâ€™s take a look at the elements in the first list. There are different kinds of ingredients.

recipe$ingredients[1]
## [[1]]
## [1] "romaine lettuce"      "black olives"         "grape tomatoes"      
## [4] "garlic"               "pepper"               "purple onion"        
## [7] "seasoning"            "garbanzo beans"       "feta cheese crumbles"

To convert the char list to character, I first need to connect the words in one element using functions from stringi package and lapply, and then unlist the entire list.

temp <- lapply(recipe$ingredients,
       function(v) stri_paste(stri_replace_all(v, "_", fixed = " "), collapse = " "))
recipe$ingredients <- unlist(temp)

There are 20 types of cuisines: Among the 39774 observations, almost 8,000 of them are Italian, above 6,000 are Mexican, more than 4000 Southern US, and Indian, French, and Chinese cuisines are around 3,000 each. The rest of them appears below 2,000 times.

ggplot(data = recipe, aes(x = reorder(cuisine, -table(cuisine)[cuisine]))) + geom_bar() + labs(x = "cuisine", y = "count") + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))

Then I take each ingredient and created a sparse matrix with only terms that are used in at least 0.1% of the documents but no more than 90% of the documents.

token_list <- tokenize_words(recipe$ingredients)
token_df <- term_list_to_df(token_list)
## Loading required package: Matrix
X <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df,min_df = 0.001, max_df = 0.90, scale = FALSE)
#dim(X)

The most frequently appeared ingredients are the commonly used spices.

freq <- sort(colSums(as.matrix(X)), decreasing=TRUE)   
# Create a frequency bar chart
wf <- data.frame(word=names(freq), freq=freq)  

ggplot(subset(wf, freq>3000), aes(x = reorder(word, -freq), y = freq)) +
          geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = -freq)) + labs(x = "ingredients", y = "frequency") +
          theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1)) 

# Create the wordcloud
set.seed(123)
wordcloud(names(freq),
          scale = c(4, 0.1), 
          freq,

          max.words = 10000, 
          random.order=FALSE, rot.per=.15,

            brewer.pal(12,"Paired"))

Classification

Glmnet

I first add class number, and divid the training and validation data set. Then I created the X matrix, with tokenize_words and tokenize_ngram. Here I not only filter the terms between 0.5% and 90%, I also scaled the rows of the data to count the frequencies.

recipe$class <- as.numeric(as.factor(recipe$cuisine)) - 1
recipe$train_id <- sample(c("train", "valid"), nrow(recipe), replace = TRUE)

temp <- lapply(recipe$ingredients,
       function(v) stri_paste(stri_replace_all(v, " ", fixed = "_"), collapse = " "))
recipe$ingredients <- unlist(temp)

token_list <- tokenize_words(recipe$ingredients)
token_df <- term_list_to_df(token_list)
X1 <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df, min_df = 0.005, max_df = 0.90,
                       scale = TRUE)
dim(X1)
## [1] 39774   423
token_list <- tokenize_ngrams(recipe$ingredients, n_min = 1, n = 4)
token_df <- term_list_to_df(token_list)
X2 <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df, min_df = 0.005, max_df = 0.90,
                       scale = TRUE)
dim(X2)
## [1] 39774  1139
X <- cbind(X1, X2)

y <- recipe$class
X_train <- X[recipe$train_id == "train",]
X_valid <- X[recipe$train_id == "valid",]
y_train <- y[recipe$train_id == "train"]
y_valid <- y[recipe$train_id == "valid"]

library(glmnet)
## Warning: package 'glmnet' was built under R version 3.4.2
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loaded glmnet 2.0-13
model <- cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, nfolds = 5, alpha = 0.9, family = "multinomial")
beta <- coef(model, s = model$lambda.1se)
beta <- Reduce(cbind, beta)
beta[apply(beta != 0, 1, any),][1:30,]

XGBoost

Then I tried trees to catch the nonlinearity.

token_list <- tokenize_words(recipe$ingredients)
#token_list[10]
token_df <- term_list_to_df(token_list)
#filter(token_df, id == 10)

X <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df,min_df = 0.005, max_df = 0.90, scale = TRUE)
y <- recipe$class

X_train <- X[recipe$train_id == "train",]
X_valid <- X[recipe$train_id == "valid",]
y_train <- y[recipe$train_id == "train"]
y_valid <- y[recipe$train_id == "valid"]

library(xgboost)
## 
## Attaching package: 'xgboost'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     slice
data_train <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(X_train), label = y_train)
data_valid <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(X_valid), label = y_valid)
watchlist <- list(train=data_train, valid=data_valid)

model <- xgb.train(data = data_train,
                 max_depth = 4, eta = 0.001, nthread = 2,
                 nrounds = 1000, objective = "multi:softmax",
                 watchlist = watchlist, num_class = 20,
                 print_every_n = 100)

Extension

The models did a pretty good job classifying different types of cuisines. So I think it might be interesting to let machine learning make some cuisines based on peoples preference and some robots can cook. It seems to be very productive. I found an interesting article: A scientist is trying to teach a neural network to cookâ€”and the results are hilariously bad
